      },
      "date": "2013-04-04 16:28:03.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI'm not finding your argument very convincing.  If a sysadmin can't handle the very simplest of rpm dependencies, then there is no way in hell they can run something as difficult to use as lustre.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "e78d1440e0bf5306fafeb124674c4dbd0145625f",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 177,
        "name": "John Hammond",
        "email": "jhammond@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "jhammond"
      },
      "date": "2013-04-04 17:06:27.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\nI agree that lustre and ldiskfs build should be as loosely coupled as possible but I do not see how this achieves that or that the benefits outweigh the cost of change.\n\nThe simplicity of prefixed names is worth preserving: \"rpm -Fvh lustre-*\" should work.\n\nMoreover, as you know, ldiskfs is not intended as a \"real\" stand alone filesystem for Linux, or at least not one that we support as such.  Therefore it belongs in the Lustre suite of rpms, albeit as an optional member.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "f6e30bf3febb9cd00ec89782e8333d7cea5797f9",
      "author": {
